<dl id="n08090e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08090e">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08090e"> 90(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> punish (punissons)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">As to the verbs, the rule is that the stem of the French present plural served as basis for the English form; thus (<i>je survis</i>), <i>nous survivons</i> &hellip; became <i>survive</i> &hellip;; thus is explained the frequent ending <i>-ish</i>, in <i>punish</i>, <i>finish</i>, etc. <small> Otto Jespersen, <a name="OJGS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#OJGS"><cite title="source">The Growth and Structure of the English Language</cite></a>, 4th ed. (Jul 1923) 101</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
